plot(Room.Board,Books,col="red")

By viewing the scatterplot, there does not seem to be a relationship between the cost of room & board and the estimated cost of books.

plot(PhD,S.F.Ratio,col="red")

By viewing the scatterplot, there does not seem to be a relationship between the percent of faculy with Ph.D.’s and the student/faculty ratio.

Question 10: Boston housing

library(MASS)
#Boston
dim(Boston)
## [1] 506  14
#fix(Boston)

There are 506 rows and 14 columns.

The rows are observations, each being a town. Each column is a variable that may affect the housing value for each town, such at the per capita crime rate by town or the average number of rooms per dwelling.

attach(Boston)
pairs(Boston)

I don’t see any clear patterns in this format.

There seems there may be a relationship between per capita crime rate and average age, median value of owner-occupied homes, and weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centers.

hist(crim,col="red",breaks=15)

hist(tax,col="red",breaks=15)

hist(ptratio,col="red",breaks=15)

There is a spike in crime rates early in the observations.

The tax rates seem pretty evenly distributed.

The pupil ratio also haa a spike, but it’s farther down in the list of observations.
